      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, you're right, I forgot to finish the sentence before the goblin decided to interrupt the explanation of the stroma! The Calvin Cycle happens in the **stroma**, the fluid-filled space surrounding the thylakoids, and it's where the magic of carbon fixation actually takes place.\n\nHere's what actually happens in the Calvin Cycle:\n\nFirst, the cycle uses the **ATP** and **NADPH** produced by the light-dependent reactions to power the process. The enzyme **Rubisco** (Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase) grabs a carbon dioxide molecule from the air and attaches it to a five-carbon sugar called **RuBP**. This creates an unstable six-carbon intermediate that immediately splits into two three-carbon molecules called **3-phosphoglycerate (3-PGA)**.\n\nNow, the real work begins. These 3-PGA molecules are converted into **G3P** (glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate) using more ATP. Most of this G3P is used to regenerate RuBP so the cycle can continue, but **one out of every six G3P molecules** is the \"surplus\" that",
